            <div class="headers-container">

                <div class="headers">

                    
                        
                        





        
        
        <h5 class="rubric"><span>Photo Essay</span></h5>
    

                        
                    

                    
                        
                        








        
            <h1 class="content-headline">Rare Scenes from 9/11</h1>
        
    


                        
                    

                    
                        
                        





 
    
         
            
                <h2 class="sub-header"><span>The day the world changed. <i>Related:</i> Read an <a href="/politics/features/2006/09/friend_excerpt200609">excerpt</a> from <i>Watching the World Change.</i></span></h2>
            
        
  



                        
                    

                    
                        
                        














    
    

    

    

    
        
    

    

    



    








      <div class="display-date">
          
              <span><span class="red">WEB EXCLUSIVE</span></span>
          

          

          
              
              
              
          

          
          

          <!-- MMMM d, yyyy -->
          
          
              
              
              September 1, 2006 
            

          
          


          
           

      </div>
  



                        
                    

                </div>

            </div>

        
        

        
        

            <div class="intro-container">

                <div class="intro">

                    
                    
                        
                        











      
  



    
        
            
            
                    
                          
                          
                    
                
        
    


    
    
    

    <div class="captioned-photo">
        


















        
        
    




    
            <div class="w"><img src="/images/politics/2006/09/poar01_wtc0609.jpg" alt="" class="featureimg"   /></div>
        




        
            <p class="caption"><i>Photograph by Rob Howard.</i></p>
        
        
        
    </div>










                        
                    

                    <div class="intro-text">

                        
                            
                            
                            










                            
                            
                        

                        
                            
                            
                            





    <div class="text">
        The terror assault of September 11, 2001, in which nearly 3,000 perished, was the most widely viewed breaking-news event in human history. And as the horrors unfolded, thousands of bystanders, professional photographers, and TV-news crews took tens of thousands of images and filled untold hours of videotape. On television alone, the scenes were witnessed that day by an estimated two billion people&mdash;a third of the human race. On the fifth anniversary of the attacks, David Friend, a <i>Vanity Fair</i> editor, releases <i>Watching the World Change: The Stories Behind the Images of 9/11</i> (Farrar, Straus and Giroux). The book examines the pivotal role that photographs play in modern life, as seen through the prism of the most tragic week in U.S. history since World War II. <i>Related:</i> Read an <a href="/politics/features/2006/09/friend_excerpt200609">excerpt</a> from <i>Watching the World Change.</i>

    </div>


                            
                            
                        

                    </div>

                </div>

            </div>

        
        

    

    
    

    
        
           
































































